Data cleaning for EOCELA

Setup

Load relevant libraries and set local environment, then get the data from AWS.

library(tidyverse)
library(aws.s3)

source('/Users/kelliemacphee/Desktop/dssg2018/cred.txt')
Sys.setenv("AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID" = access_key,
           "AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY" = secret_key,
           "AWS_DEFAULT_REGION" = "us-west-2")

get_bucket('dssg2018')
data <- s3read_using(FUN = read.csv, object = "s3://dssg2018/rawdata/DPS_EOCELA_1112-1617.csv")

CourseFinal entries look unnecessarily complicated. Do years agree with years in the other column?

for (course in levels(data$CourseFinal)){
  temp <- data[data$CourseFinal==course,]
  years <- unique(temp$SpringYear)
  print(paste(course, "happened in", years))
}
## [1] "American Lit Course Final happened in 2012"
## [1] "American Lit Course Final 1213 happened in 2013"

## [1] "World Lit Course Final 1314 happened in 2014"
## [1] "World Lit Course Final 1415 happened in 2015"
## [1] "World Lit Course Final 1516 happened in 2016"

Answer: yes. Lets simplify these CourseFinal names, then, to just the course name (and Part or 2, if necessary). Note that in cases when the year isnt specified, that means the exam occurred in 2012.

levels(data$CourseFinal) <- gsub(" Course Final \\d{4}", "", levels(data$CourseFinal))
levels(data$CourseFinal) <- gsub(" Course Final", "", levels(data$CourseFinal))

# delete any trailing white spaces
levels(data$CourseFinal) <- gsub(" $", "", levels(data$CourseFinal))

levels(data$CourseFinal)
## [1] "American Lit" "English I"    "English II"   "English III" 
## [5] "Intro to Lit" "World Lit"
